console.log(0 || "Hello");
console.log("" || "World");
console.log("JS" && 100);
console.log(null && "Test");



Explanation

0 || "Hello"

|| (OR) returns the first truthy value.

0 is falsy, so JavaScript moves to "Hello".
Output: Hello

"" || "World"

"" (empty string) is falsy.

So "World" is returned.
Output: World

"JS" && 100

&& (AND) returns the second value if the first is truthy.

"JS" is truthy, so it returns 100.

Output: 100

null && "Test"

&& returns the first falsy value it finds.

null is falsy, so it stops and returns null.

Output: null
